    "jays": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Blue Jays",
      "league": "MLB",
      "record": "8-13",
      "detail": "4th in AL East",
      "live_strip": null,
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "They were dead. Then, for one inning, they remembered how to swing. The Blue Jays clawed back from the brink yesterday with <strong>an eight-run explosion in the first inning against Arizona</strong>, salvaging a split in the series with a 10-4 victory after dropping the first two games. It's the kind of performance that whispers possibility in a clubhouse that's been suffocating under the weight of injuries and incompetence. At 8-13, Toronto sits fourth in the AL East, 4.5 games back, with a playoff seed that reads like a punchline: 11th. Six consecutive series losses had the fanbase reaching for the liquor cabinet. One win doesn't erase that rot - not yet.\n\nBut it matters. Kevin Gausman took the mound with the season on life support, and the lineup finally delivered the kind of violence this team needs to stay breathing. The question now isn't whether they can win one game. It's whether they can string together enough of them before the hole becomes a grave. <strong>They head to Anaheim Tuesday night to face the Angels</strong> - another chance to build momentum, another test of whether yesterday's outburst was catharsis or mirage.",
        "updated": "Updated April 20, 2026"
      },
